{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"odd-vortex-elbow","description":"## Context\nrebar has no general mechanism to apply an idempotent setup/format change to an ALREADY-EXISTING install. Its init-time `_migrate_*` functions (e.g. `_migrate_gc_config`) only run at `init`/re-init, so a change shipped after a store was initialized never reaches it unless someone re-inits — exactly the gap the `gc.auto=0` legacy-store issue exposed (fixed operationally this session; the mechanism is what's missing). Discovered from that gc discussion.\n\nThis session researched converged OSS practice (SQLite `user_version`, git-annex `annex.version`, Rails/Django/Alembic/Flyway ledgers, IndexedDB `onupgradeneeded`, Terraform state upgrades, Ansible/Puppet/Chef desired-state). Two schools: A = versioned/tracked/ordered/run-once (for irreversible/data-backfill changes); B = idempotent \"ensure\" / desired-state (for stateless convergent config invariants). The `gc.auto` class is textbook School B. Key insight (git-annex's documented regret): a per-clone-local version marker can't tell on merge that two clones diverged — but rebar shares every write through a committed branch, so a future A-tier could carry a committed store-format version that coordinates across clones.\n\nScope decision: build the **B tier** now; capture the **A tier** (committed store-format version + ordered ledger, fail-closed on too-new store) as documented future work. HARD CONSTRAINT: no degradation of hot-path ticket operations.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- A documented, reusable idempotent \"ensure\" mechanism applies per-environment setup changes to existing installs at non-hot entry points, provably never executing on the ticket-mutation hot path, discoverable and reusable by future sessions.\n\n## Workstreams\n- WS-M1: an idempotent `ensure_*` step registry (generalize init's `_migrate_gc_config` / gitignore / gitattributes / merge-driver into a registry of self-checking, re-run-safe steps). No version marker required for pure ensures (desired-state).\n- WS-M2: trigger wiring (Option C) — ensures RUN only at non-hot entry points: `init`/re-init (existing), `fsck`, a new `rebar doctor`/`upgrade` command, and MCP-server / reconciler process startup (paid once per process). The per-ticket-operation hot path NEVER executes a sweep.\n- WS-M3: a write-path-only, piggybacked staleness HINT (fold the applied-ensure-version compare onto a local `.rebar/` read the write path already does, e.g. the HLC state read) that prints a one-line \"run `rebar doctor`\" nudge when stale. Pure reads (show/list/search) untouched.\n- WS-M4: documentation — a first-class `docs/migrations.md` (how to add an ensure step, where it runs, the marker, the performance contract) so future sessions discover and reuse it; note the A-tier future extension + the committed-version-marker recommendation.\n- WS-M5: tests — idempotency of ensures; the staleness-hint behavior; and a HOT-PATH REGRESSION test asserting the mutation path may detect-and-hint but NEVER invokes the ensure sweep.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] An idempotent `ensure_*` registry generalizes the init-time `_migrate_*` steps; each step is re-run-safe\n- [ ] Ensures execute only at non-hot entry points (init/re-init, fsck, `rebar doctor`/upgrade, server startup); a `rebar doctor`/`upgrade` command exists\n- [ ] A write-path-only, piggybacked staleness hint points users to `rebar doctor`; pure reads are untouched\n- [ ] Hot-path regression test: ticket-mutation ops may hint but never execute an ensure sweep (no added hot-path I/O beyond an existing read)\n- [ ] `docs/migrations.md` documents the pattern for reuse; the A-tier (committed store-format version + ordered ledger, fail-closed on too-new) is captured as future work\n- [ ] gc.auto normalization is documented as the reference example ensure step","id":"9ccb-27ee-24dd-4944","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"epic","title":"First-class migration pattern: idempotent per-environment ensure-registry (B tier)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782865665256694001,"uuid":"512a9a69-9614-4a3e-b7d7-e43e5561aaf2"}